<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-06-04T05:44:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-06-04T05:44:00-05:00" n="271" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d271">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">882.00/824: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Liberia</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Carter</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Monrovia</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-06-04T10:00:00-00:44">June 4, 1930—10
                                a.m.</date><lb/>[Received 1:27 p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>75. I saw President King yesterday, taking occasion to assure the
                            President of American friendship, and I stated further my assurance that
                            the good offices of the United States would be forthcoming in the
                            present admitted crisis in the event he had to call for them.<note n="1" xml:id="d271fn1">See also <ref target="#pg_394">pp. 394</ref>
                                ff.</note></p>
                        <p>He seemed to appreciate this attitude.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Carter</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>